As a result, photos and TV film of health workers and older people happily receiving Pfizer inoculations on December 8 were hailed as the beginning of a fightback and, hopefully, a return to normality in 2021.
But just as hopes rose for an eventual end to the scourge of Covid, the spotlight focused on another crisis — Britain’s future relations with the continent of Europe.
When a slim majority of Britons voted narrowly four years ago for Brexit (Britain’s exit from the European Union), supporters happily declared that the country could make a new trade deal with Europe on better terms, or if necessary, go it alone. However, the grinding pace of current negotiations is telling a different story.





Fishing rights
At the time of writing, significant differences remain on issues such as fishing rights (who can fish where and catch what), the rules of fair competition known as the level playing field, enforcement of agreements, and the Northern Ireland border question.
It is probably little consolation to those who voted to stay in Europe to learn of the trend demonstrated by recent opinion polls on the Brexit question.
A sampling of opinion on November 30 showed that if given the choice today, 74 per cent would now vote to remain in Europe, against 67 per cent who would still leave. A poll taken five days later increased the lead for Remain from six points to nine.



