Aiming to crack down on out-of-control gambling, the government has ordered that the age limit for playing the National Lottery be raised from 16 years to 18 from next October.
The number of problem gamblers in the UK, those who play beyond their means, is estimated at 340,000, many of them teenagers. They are more likely to come from a black background than a white or Asian one and from the poor rather than the well off.
Some desperate gamblers resort to theft and violence or end up in hospital with psychotic conditions. Campaigners want gambling abuse to be seen as a public health issue like smoking, obesity and alcoholism.
Culture Secretary Oliver Dowden said last week that the betting industry had evolved “at breakneck speed”. He promised that the government would undertake a wide-ranging review to tackle “problem gambling in all its forms to protect children and vulnerable people”.
Sports Minister Nigel Huddleston noted that patterns of play had changed in recent years, with a shift towards online games. The increased age limit would help ensure that the National Lottery was not a gateway to problem gambling, he said.
